<TEXT>
an estimated 150000 people will 
develop aids this year doubling the number of estimated aids cases 
worldwide since the epidemic began the world health organization 
said sunday 
aids is changing the world said jonathan mann director of 
the world health organizations aids program it has become a key 
part of the history of our time 
he spoke at the opening session of the fourth international 
conference on aids in stockholm 
the number of aids cases officially reported to the world health 
organization stood at 75392 on jan 12 and 96433 as of june 1 
the number of actual cases is estimated to be 200000 mann said 
although aids was not identified until 1981 the origins of the 
epidemic have been traced back to the 1970s 
a virus spread across the world and we didnt even know it 
existed mann said it is or should be shocking to our 
modern pride that such a global expansion could occur without even 
being detected 
mann said the five years after 1981 marked a period of 
extraordinary discovery in which the ways in which aids spread 
were identified the virus was isolated and an aids antibody test 
was developed 
lars kallings chairman of the aids conference said the meeting 
allowed scientists to assemble their findings like the pieces of a 
jigsaw puzzle into a large picture of the aids epidemic 
im afraid that the picture in its entirety will be 
frightening he said 
mann described the three distinct patterns of aids spread that 
make up the worldwide epidemic pattern i he said is that seen in 
the united states and western europe where the disease appeared 
first in homosexuals and bisexuals 
heterosexual transmission is growing in those areas the virus 
is spreading rapidly among drug abusers through their shared 
needles but blood supplies have now been made safe by screening 
for the virus 
pattern ii mann said characterizes africa and parts of latin 
america and the caribbean where the aids spread has been 
predominantly among heterosexuals 
pattern iii refers to the delayed spread of aids in eastern 
europe the middle east north africa and most countries in asia 
and the pacific 
only 1 percent of the aids cases reported to the world health 
organization come from pattern iii countries mann said 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome is a disease in which a 
virus attacks the bodys immune system leaving victims susceptible 
to a wide variety of infections and cancers 
