<TEXT>
seventeen years after it first opened in new 
york godspell has come home with its simplicity good humor 
and joyous sense of wonder intact 
the production which arrived sunday at the lambs theater is 
not so much a revival as a repolishing of the original material 
while adding bits and pieces from todays follies and foibles to 
bring it up to date ronald reagan is here so are jim and tammy 
bakker even pee wee herman gets into the act although he and the 
other names from current events are not the essential part of the 
story 
the musical remains a carefully crafted piece of street theater 
that seeks to instruct if not convert the book devised by 
johnmichael tebelak follows the gospel according to st matthew 
reinterpreting the live of jesus as well as the parables he told 
tebelaks jesus is a clown a harlequin with a heart painted on 
his forehead and a big red superman s on his chest hes a 
teacher and his lessons come right from matthews version of the 
bible he reinterprets many of the most famous parables such as the 
prodigal son 
that reinterpretation is accomplished through a series of 
vaudeville turns directed with a sure sense of style and wit by don 
scardino theres low comedy high camp and just about every type 
of dumb joke in between but the concoction works primarily 
because of scardinos inventiveness and the exuberant score most 
of it written by stephen schwartz 
godspell remains the composers most beguiling work 
schwartz later went on to write such musicals as pippin the 
magic show and the bakers wife but it is in his first show 
that he found the best inspiration from an anthem like prepare 
ye the way of the lord to an obvious uptempo show stopper like 
we beseech thee schwartz tailored his music to a young 
enthusiastic cast and still managed to produce one song day by 
day which found a life outside the musical 
its been fashionable to dismiss godspell for its naivete 
and simplemindedness but this revival contains some surprising 
moments of power particularly at the end of the evening when jesus 
is betrayed by judas 
the scene is memorable for a fine bit of acting by jeffrey 
steefel as the street version of the messiah and robert mcneill as 
his betrayer but then the entire cast exudes a precision and 
passion uncommon in most revivals they are among some of the best 
young musical comedy talent around 
the others include laura dean a bewitching seductress anne 
bobby a sweetfaced singer trini alvarado a striking woman with 
a low sexy voice bill damaschke a goofy likable performer 
angel jemmott a fine comedian and a belter as well eddie korbich 
a real songanddance hoofer mia korf who manages to make day 
by day sound fresh and harold perrineau jr a sturdy soul 
singer 
the scenery by allison campbell is a generic street scene while 
the costumes by david c woolard are thriftshop eccentric making 
up in color what they lack in high fashion 
but this resurrection of godspell has plenty of style high 
spirits and sense of fun which make it impossible to resist it 
should win plenty of new converts 
</TEXT>
