<TEXT>
a study commissioned by the mexican government 
says mexico should strengthen its ties to the us automobile 
industry by making it easier to export cars assembled in mexico and 
by upgrading its auto parts industry according to a report 
published sunday 
the detroit news which obtained the study said it notes that a 
closer alliance between the two nations auto industries might 
develop only if mexico distinguished itself from japan south korea 
and other nations competing in the market 
the study conducted by the consulting firm boozallen amp 
hamilton inc was commissioned last year by the mexican government 
and the bank of mexico as part of efforts to obtain world bank 
loans for industrial restructuring 
the mexican government must differentiate mexico from other 
countries brazil taiwan korea and japan in the eyes of the us 
congress and the us public stressing proximity cultural ties 
common problems and the long period of constructive 
relationships the study said 
if us protectionism grows and mexico is lumped together with 
japan and korea in retaliatory us trade legislation all of the 
recommendations in this report are moot it said 
the study estimated that salaried auto workers in mexico are 
paid 20 percent to 25 percent of what their us counterparts 
receive 
the study argued that the lower costs were part of mexican 
economic advantages within a north american auto production system 
that saves jobs for us workers 
without access to mexico to selectively provide lowcost 
labor as part of the overall process more vehicles and parts 
would be obtained from brazil and various far east countries with 
the consequent loss of both us and mexican jobs the study said 
boozallen recommended that mexico immediately upgrade its auto 
partsmaking industy which accounted for more than half of that 
nations 900 million auto exports trade surplus in 1986 
the study also called for easing regulations on companies 
already assembling cars in mexico to encourage more exports to the 
us it also recommended that mexico establish a technical center 
in detroit to keep pace with technological developments 
the big three us automakers each have assembly engine and 
parts plants in mexico chrysler corp and general motors corp 
spokesmen said they were unaware of plans to increase investments 
there a ford motor co spokesman said company doesnt discuss 
possible investments 
boozallen said mexico would have to convince the united auto 
workers union that an automotive alliance would benefit both 
countries 
but uaw secretarytreasurer bill casstevens said the union 
remained opposed to mexican auto investments that he said exploited 
workers there and caused the loss of us jobs 
